The grant of leave under the present rule involves similar considerations to those that apply to a defendant’s application (under UCPR 
r 11.7(2)
) to set aside external service. They include (i) whether the external service was authorised by the rules and (ii) whether the Supreme Court is an inappropriate forum. The latter criterion has a somewhat lesser emphasis than the “clearly inappropriate forum” criterion that applies to stay applications under CPA s 67: Voth v Manildra Flour Mills Pty Ltd (1990) 171 CLR 538 at 562–4; 97 ALR 124; 65 ALJR 83;  BC9002894 : Oceanic Sun Line Special Shipping Co Inc v Fay (1988) 165 CLR 197 at 247; 79 ALR 9; 62 ALJR 389;  BC8802600 ; Hyde v Agar (1998) 45 NSWLR 487; (1999) Aust Torts Reports 81-495;  BC9805415 ; Regie National des Usines Renault SA v Zhang (2002) 210 CLR 491; 187 ALR 1; [2002] HCA 10;  BC200200802 at [23]–[25] . Nevertheless those principles (which are discussed at 
[s 67.55]
) will apply to the grant of leave under the present rule — with some allowance for the difference in emphasis: see Studorp Ltd v Robinson [2012] NSWCA 382;  BC201210606 at [5] and [62] .
